# UK English (en-GB)

OscarWatch uses **British English** for operator-facing text. Default UI culture is **`en-GB`** (`LocalizationCulture.DefaultLanguage`).

## Where this applies

- `OscarWatch/Resources/Strings.resx` (and translations when adding parallel keys)
- `help/**/*.html`, `README.md`, operator docs
- Accessibility strings, tooltips, menu labels, dialogues, error messages
- Commit messages and PR descriptions for this repo (when writing prose for the user)

## Spelling and wording

| Prefer (UK) | Avoid (US) |
|-------------|------------|
| visualiser | visualizer |
| labelled | labeled |
| colour, centre, metre, kilometre | color, center, meter, kilometer |
| grey / greyline | gray |
| dialogue (UI window in docs) | dialog (in prose) |
| application / app | program (for software) |

Use **English (UK)** in the language picker label. Keep **License** when citing AGPL or other proper legal names.

## Localisation

- Add user-visible English to `Strings.resx`; avoid new hardcoded English in controls or view models.
- Use `LocalizationService` / `loc:Localize` — do not assume `en-US` culture.
- Tests that need English culture should use **`en-GB`**, not `en-US`, unless explicitly testing another locale.

## Exceptions (do not “UK-ify”)

- **Code identifiers** (class names, resource keys, filenames) — rename only when refactoring, not for spelling.
- **Brands and protocols** (ICOM, CI-V, COM port, PayPal, GitHub).
- **Diagnostics / logs** labelled “English” for support bundles (`RigStatusText.ToEnglish`, etc.).
